What is the structure of your dataset?

The dataset given to us is a tidy dataset and it has 1599 observations with 13 variables for each one. All of the observations are numerical. The first one is used as an index. The quality variable has 6 values: 4, 5, 6, 7, 8. Also, The median quality is 6. Most wines have a pH of 3.4 or higher.The median percent alcohol content is 10.20 and the max percent alcohol content is 14.90.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The basic question that comes to mind, with a dataset like this is, how do chemical properties define the quality of the red wine? The main features in the data set are pH and quality. I want to identify which features are optimal for predicting the quality of a wine. I suspect pH and some combination of the other variables can be used to grade the quality of wines.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

After doing some research on the internet, I believe volatile acidity (the amount of acetic acid in wine) and alcohol (the percent alcohol content of the wine) probably contribute most to the quality

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I made a new variable rating and basically classified the wine as bad,normal or good based on its quality value. I also found out that the fixed and volotile acidity actually represent the tartartic and acetic acid content. I added these and citric acid value to create a new total variable

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?

Having visualized acitric acid and volatile acidity data, I observed some unusual distributions but not bizzare, so I guess this fact may have some correlation with the quality of red wine. Since the data is clean, I did not perform any cleaning process or modification of the data.

Bivariate Plots Section

To get quick overview of how quality/rating is affected by the other variables, I have created bivariate box plots for each of them. (Both quality and rating)

In the above plots, we build bivariate boxplots for each of the 12 variables with respect to the quality variable. We also mark the mean and the jitter for better understanding. These plots are important as it helps us understand how each individual parameter might be affecting the quality of
the wine. We learn that :

  1. Volatile acidity goes down as quality increases.
  2. Citric acid content goes up as quality increases.
  3. Residual sugar does not have a direct relation with quality.
  4. Mean Density is decreasing as we go up in quality.
  5. Alcohol level generally goes up as quality increases.

Now we plot bivariate boxplots for each variable with respect to the rating variable. This will help us understand the variations as a class.

We can confirm our previous results with these generated boxplots. The results we got wrt quality variable stays true for rating variable and makes analysis clearer.

INSIGHTS

Using the above plots, we can theorise a few trends about wine and its constituents. Better wine usually has :
1. High fixed acidity and low volatile acidity.
2. Are more acidic in nature (Lower ph).
3. Higher sulphates and alcohol content.

We will confirm our hypothesis using correlation statistics below.

Its interesting to note that different type of acid affected the wine quality.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset?

I observed a negative relationships between quality level and volatile acidity, and positive correlation between quality level and alcohol. This makes sense because, because We tend to grade stronger wines as high quality, whereas wines with low percent alcohol are not graded as such. High volatile acidity is also perceived to be undesirable because it negatively impacts the taste of wines. The sulphate measurements have a mild effect on the quality score. This was something I didnt expect.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

Yes, I observed positive relationship between density and fixed acidity, positive relationship between fixed acidity and citric acid, and negative relationship between pH and fixed acidity.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

Citric acid and fixed acidity have a strong positive correlation of 0.67, while citrict acid and volatile acidity have a moderate negative correlation of -0.55.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One - Wine quality spectrum

Description One

The distribution of red wine quality appears to be normally distributed. Most of the wines are rated 5 and 6 (normal or average quality). Even though the rating scale is between 0 and 10, no wine is rated 1, 2, 9 or 10. That is, No one recorded a perfect wine.

Plot Two - ? Alcohol ? Good ? Bad ?

Description Two

The above boxplot demonstrates the effect of alcohol content on wine quality. Generally, higher alcohol content correlated with higher wine quality. However, as the outliers and intervals show, alchol content alone does not guarantee quality wine.

Plot Three - How to get a good wine ?

Description Three

Correlation tests showed that alcohol and volatile acidity was two parameters that affected wine quality. This plot showes us that out of the two, alcohol has more importance. Low volatile acidity is the mark of a good wine and a few outliers of wine with high volatile acidity did have high alcohol content too. In conclusion, we can say that higher alcohol content and a lower volatile acidity can help produce a good wine.

Reflection

Through this EDA project, I was able to understand the characteristics that determinewine quality, like its alcohol content, sulphates, and acidity level.

It is important to note, however, that wine quality is ultimately a subjective quality, albeit measured by wine experts. A brief reading has led me to understand that while a wine can be differentiated as good and bad usually,even wine tasters differ on extreme cases as each may appreciate different tastes.

The graphs I made adequately illustrate upto a point, factors that can help make good wines good and bad wines bad. More data about wines with quality below 3 and above 7 can be helpful.

LIMITATIONS

This dataset is incomplete. A more complete dataset can be created if we added information to indicate say, forexample, the type of grapes used, age of the wine etc. Also, working with this kind of dataset would become much easier if you had a domain knowledge about wines and the effect of the constituents. Additional inferential statistics could be done to quantify and confirm the analysis.
